but we got a lotta ground to cover.

17
00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:49.980
All right, I'm gonna start this lecture

18
00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:51.750
with an AES question.

19
00:00:51.750 --> 00:00:54.360
You have a 14-year-old female, arrives at the triage area

20
00:00:54.360 --> 00:00:57.270
of your local rural hospital in the emergency department

21
00:00:57.270 --> 00:01:00.030
with worsening abdominal pain for the past two days.

22
00:01:00.030 --> 00:01:02.220
The patient's parents are out of town for the day

23
00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:04.230
and unavailable by cell phone.

24
00:01:04.230 --> 00:01:06.660
The patient is accompanied by her 17-year-old sister.

25
00:01:06.660 --> 00:01:09.060
The triage nurse asks you for your advice.

26
00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:11.373
In this case, you would recommend,

27
00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:15.540
A, do not perform an H&amp;P on the patient

28
00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:17.520
until you can get hold of those parents,

29
00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:19.140
B, obtain a history from the patient,

30
00:01:19.140 --> 00:01:21.030
but don't perform any physical exam

31
00:01:21.030 --> 00:01:24.450
and don't touch her until the parent says it's okay,

32
00:01:24.450 --> 00:01:27.870
C, inquire if the patient could be pregnant, and if so,

33
00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:29.640
then you can proceed with further care,

34
00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:32.910
or D, perform an H&amp;P and proceed with diagnostic testing

35
00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:34.800
if there is concern for acute pathology

36
00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:36.850
that can worsen if a delay were to occur.

37
00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:43.440
This is right. Do the right thing.

38
00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:46.410
Treat the patient. Treat the patient, absolutely.

39
00:01:46.410 --> 00:01:49.140
And going back, EMTALA was initially known

40
00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:50.520
as the anti-dumping rule.

41
00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:53.100
In 1986, it was enacted.

42
00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:56.370
It was designed to say, "Oh, you private hospitals,

43
00:01:56.370 --> 00:01:58.800
you can't dish off the uninsured

44
00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:01.560
to the county or public hospitals."

45
00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:03.600
Every emergency department in the United States

46
00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:07.380
has to accept patients irregardless

47
00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:10.020
of their financial status.

48
00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:12.810
Now, they have to at least be able to stabilize

49
00:02:12.810 --> 00:02:16.230
and treat the patients under EMTALA.

50
00:02:16.230 --> 00:02:20.610
All right, now some, such as my hospital even,

51
00:02:20.610 --> 00:02:22.620
we're a community hospital but we don't have all services.

52
00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:25.200
We are allowed, after we have done our best

53
00:02:25.200 --> 00:02:26.820
to stabilize that patient,

54
00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:29.790
to transfer them to the tertiary care center

55
00:02:29.790 --> 00:02:33.210
where they have appropriate facilities.

56
00:02:33.210 --> 00:02:35.280
So for example, we don't have a neurosurgeon in our place,

57
00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:37.530
but if we need a neurosurgeon,

58
00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:40.590
under EMTALA, we can obviously transfer the patient.

59
00:02:40.590 --> 00:02:45.180
The accepting hospital has to accept the patient

60
00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:48.960
if they have capacity and capabilities of doing so.

61
00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:50.460
If you're at the local rural hospital

62
00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:52.680
or my hospital before I transfer them,

63
00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:55.800
I have to do my best to provide whatever care it is

64
00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:58.440
to those patients, okay?

65
00:02:58.440 --> 00:02:59.640
And that's EMTALA.

66
00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.700
Also EMTALA, it talks about treating minors.

67
00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:05.670
Essentially a minor may request

68
00:03:05.670 --> 00:03:07.410
an emergency evaluation and treatment,

69
00:03:07.410 --> 00:03:11.670
and it's your job and duty to try to stabilize

70
00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:13.053
and evaluate that patient.

71
00:03:14.430 --> 00:03:16.263
All right, next question.

72
00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:18.870
You're on a plane ride when a passenger

73
00:03:18.870 --> 00:03:20.580
suddenly becomes unresponsive.

74
00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:22.203
Which statement below is true?

75
00:03:24.270 --> 00:03:25.830
The person next to you on the plane

76
00:03:25.830 --> 00:03:30.000
suddenly goes kaboom, unconscious and is on the floor.

77
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.670
You should immediately start chest compressions.

78
00:03:32.670 --> 00:03:35.760
B, you should check a pulse, and if not present,

79
00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:37.260
open the airway, give two rescue breaths,

80
00:03:37.260 --> 00:03:39.030
and start chest compressions.

81
00:03:39.030 --> 00:03:41.490
C, you should check a pulse, and if none present,

82
00:03:41.490 --> 00:03:42.900
just start compressions.

83
00:03:42.900 --> 00:03:44.790
D, you're aware that Good Samaritan laws

84
00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:46.140
protect you in all 50 states,

85
00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:48.780
but don't get involved because such laws do not exist

86
00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:49.743
during air flight.

87
00:03:54.870 --> 00:03:56.850
You should check a pulse, and if there's nothing there,

88
00:03:56.850 --> 00:04:00.120
just start pounding on the chest, all right?

89
00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:03.870
So I put in a couple of just BLS

90
00:04:03.870 --> 00:04:06.060
and ALS questions because David noted

91
00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:07.710
a couple of years ago when he took the boards,

92
00:04:07.710 --> 00:04:10.620
he had one or two questions on BLS and ACLS.

93
00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:15.120
So just to update you very, very quickly,

94
00:04:15.120 --> 00:04:18.720
when someone goes kaboom unconscious, it's no longer ABC.

95
00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.280
It's now CAB.

96
00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:22.560
You go unconscious, you just start compressions.

97
00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:24.510
Now, the general public is not encouraged

98
00:04:24.510 --> 00:04:26.520
to do a pulse check 'cause they don't know

99
00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:27.600
what they're checking for.

100
00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:29.280
You and I, as healthcare professionals,

101
00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:30.390
are encouraged to do a pulse check,

102
00:04:30.390 --> 00:04:32.640
and if there's nothing there, start the compressions.

103
00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:35.340
So it's CAB, and you keep doing that

104
00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:37.320
until you can figure out what the rhythm is.

105
00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:40.350
You get a defibrillator or a monitor nearby,

106
00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:43.920
and then you decide is this patient in a shockable rhythm

107
00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:46.110
or is it a non-shockable rhythm?

108
00:04:46.110 --> 00:04:48.660
So the non-shockable rhythms are very easy.

109
00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:50.700
It's asystole or PEA.

110
00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:54.660
Asystole, unfortunately, you got asystole, you're dead.

111
00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:57.330
You continue CPR and the only drug you give is epinephrine.

112
00:04:57.330 --> 00:04:58.890
Atropine is out.

113
00:04:58.890 --> 00:05:03.890
For PEA, you're encouraged to do the five Ts, six Hs.

114
00:05:04.170 --> 00:05:06.420
Try to identify an underlying source

115
00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:09.090
and treat accordingly if possible.

116
00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:12.480
When it comes to shockable rhythms,

117
00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:15.810
you have Vfib and V-tach, and what do you do right away?

118
00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:17.220
If you see one of those, you just shock.

119
00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:18.810
You just defibrillate at 200 joules,

120
00:05:18.810 --> 00:05:21.540
go back to CPR, shock again.

121
00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:23.760
Epi is the drug of choice, shock again,

122
00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:25.140
and then when you finally get down,

123
00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:27.540
if they're still in Vfib or V-tach,

124
00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:30.723
amiodarone is the antiarrhythmic of choice.

125
00:05:31.710 --> 00:05:32.543
I put this in.

126
00:05:32.543 --> 00:05:35.100
I believe Dr. Firnhaber is gonna cover this more in detail

127
00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:39.330
during his discussion of the arrhythmias,

128
00:05:39.330 --> 00:05:42.690
but I just want to make sure you have clear in your head

129
00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:45.000
the difference between defibrillation

130
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.420
and electrical synchronized cardioversion.

131
00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.270
So the first three there,

132
00:05:51.270 --> 00:05:55.320
rapid Afib, A flutter, or monomorphic V-tach,

133
00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:57.570
if the patient is unstable,

134
00:05:57.570 --> 00:06:00.150
you're going to cardiovert, okay?

135
00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:04.950
I recently had a young man in the ER who had a Afib

136
00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:07.710
and his rate was like 280, completely unstable.

137
00:06:07.710 --> 00:06:09.360
We had to immediately cardiovert him,

138
00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:11.280
a synchronized cardioversion.

139
00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:15.420
You defibrillate with polymorphic V-tach or Vfib.

140
00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:17.163
That's down below, okay?

141
00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:20.220
And I alluded to Good Samaritan laws.

142
00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:22.740
Just recognize you're covered in all 50 states

143
00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:27.740
as well as up in the air for under Good Samaritan laws,

144
00:06:28.740 --> 00:06:30.510
and the only time you'll get into trouble

145
00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:33.420
is if you do gross, willful or wanton negligence

146
00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:37.600
or you do things in lack of good faith

147
00:06:39.102 --> 00:06:40.410
or you decide to send a bill.

148
00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:41.490
Once you send a bill, forget it.

149
00:06:41.490 --> 00:06:44.673
Good Samaritan laws are out. Don't send a bill, okay?

150
00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:48.180
You are allowed to accept a gift, but don't send a bill.

151
00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:49.470
All right, shock.

152
00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:53.280
All right, you know the four types of shock.

153
00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:54.510
I don't need to go through those,

154
00:06:54.510 --> 00:06:58.770
although there's such an emphasis on sepsis.

155
00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:01.560
How many of you do hospital medicine or in the hospital?

156
00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:04.189
Aren't you, like, tired of the whole sepsis thing by now?

157
00:07:04.189 --> 00:07:05.022
<v Attendee>Yeah.</v>

158
00:07:05.022 --> 00:07:06.810
<v ->Oh, yeah, everything is septic,</v>

159
00:07:06.810 --> 00:07:10.050
and you get the alerts on your EHR, alert, alert, alert,

160
00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:12.720
and they're all false alarms and, oh yeah, I gotcha.

161
00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:15.060
So I'll just do this real quick.

162
00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:19.230
The sepsis definition, don't memorize, okay?

163
00:07:19.230 --> 00:07:22.560
Just putting it in there for completeness sake.

164
00:07:22.560 --> 00:07:25.477
This is the latest, quote, definition of sepsis,

165
00:07:25.477 --> 00:07:27.660
"a life-threatening organ dysfunction."

166
00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:29.280
Septic shock is the same thing,

167
00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:31.830
but now you've got circulatory collapse.

168
00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:34.290
Note that the whole SIRS thing,

169
00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:38.670
SIRS is not part of the definition, okay?

170
00:07:38.670 --> 00:07:41.220
All right, so you have these sepsis scores,

171
00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:43.143
SIRS being one of them.

172
00:07:44.070 --> 00:07:47.460
Just note all these scores are generally terrible.

173
00:07:47.460 --> 00:07:50.430
All right, SIRS has got terribly poor sensitivity

174
00:07:50.430 --> 00:07:51.870
and specificity.

175
00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:54.510
I mean, if you have the flu,

176
00:07:54.510 --> 00:07:57.600
you're gonna meet SIRS criteria, right?

177
00:07:57.600 --> 00:07:59.550
You're not septic, right?

178
00:07:59.550 --> 00:08:01.710
You've got the flu or COVID or whatever.

179
00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:03.150
I mean, you've got something benign.

180
00:08:03.150 --> 00:08:04.530
All right, well, whatever.

181
00:08:04.530 --> 00:08:07.170
SOFA scores, qSOFA scores, same thing.

182
00:08:07.170 --> 00:08:09.450
They're just scoring systems.

183
00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:13.863
They're not part of the definition, all right?

184
00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:16.110
What they could ask you,

185
00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:16.997
I don't think they'll ask you anything on that

186
00:08:16.997 --> 00:08:19.620
'cause it's, you know, it's up in the air,

187
00:08:19.620 --> 00:08:22.380
but what they could ask you is managing sepsis.

188
00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:23.880
That one I could see them asking,

189
00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.650
and you know this hopefully by now.

190
00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:27.900
You get your lactate levels. You get your blood cultures.

191
00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:31.980
You start the antibiotics early, and if you are shocky,

192
00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:36.930
then you start a fluid bolus of 30 mills per kilogram,

193
00:08:36.930 --> 00:08:38.610
and if you're still shocky after that,

194
00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:42.153
then the vasopressor of choice is norepinephrine.

195
00:08:43.170 --> 00:08:44.913
All right, on to stroke and TIA.

196
00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:50.400
So this is one I wanna cover in my remaining 18 minutes.

197
00:08:50.400 --> 00:08:52.740
I wanna go through stroke risk factors and prevention.

198
00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:54.840
That's what we do, primary prevention,

199
00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:57.540
what to do if you have a patient with acute stroke, TIA,

200
00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:01.140
and then secondary prevention of strokes in TIA.

201
00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:01.973
All right.

202
00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:08.330
Back to just basic pathophysiology, talking about strokes.

203
00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:11.970
Two general types, ischemic,

204
00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:13.830
not enough blood going to your brain.

205
00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:15.870
Vast majority of strokes are that type,

206
00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:19.200
or you decide to hemorrhage into your brain.

207
00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:22.110
Of the ischemic types, you see about 2/3 of those

208
00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:24.690
are gonna be because you got a thrombosis,

209
00:09:24.690 --> 00:09:26.070
a thrombotic problem.

210
00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:28.470
The other remaining 1/3 is because you had

211
00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:33.300
that cardioembolic event that went upstream, okay?

212
00:09:33.300 --> 00:09:35.160
Hemorrhagic, you have blood inside your brain

213
00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:38.340
from one of two reasons: intracerebral, subarachnoid.

214
00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:41.490
So the classic stroke risk factors,

215
00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:43.380
you know them, you love them:

216
00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:45.630
hypertension, Afib, diabetes, smoking.

217
00:09:45.630 --> 00:09:48.360
Yeah, you know them. There's the non-modifiable ones.

218
00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:50.370
You can't do anything about your age or your family history,

219
00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:52.980
and there's some uncommon ones I'll just list at the end,

220
00:09:52.980 --> 00:09:55.380
but let me just go through, I just highlighted two of them:

221
00:09:55.380 --> 00:09:57.150
hypertension, and Afib.

222
00:09:57.150 --> 00:09:59.460
Why did I highlight hypertension?

223
00:09:59.460 --> 00:10:02.490
'Cause hypertension is the big bad player

224
00:10:02.490 --> 00:10:05.250
on your brain over time.

225
00:10:05.250 --> 00:10:07.710
Not that one day the patient has

226
00:10:07.710 --> 00:10:09.217
a hypertensive urgency in their blood pressure.

227
00:10:09.217 --> 00:10:10.950
"Oh my God, it's 180 over 80.

228
00:10:10.950 --> 00:10:13.050
My God, you gotta go to the ER and they gotta fix that!"

229
00:10:13.050 --> 00:10:15.600
Don't do that, please, okay?

230
00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:17.970
Don't do that 'cause all I can do

231
00:10:17.970 --> 00:10:20.640
is screw up your patient ER if you do that.

232
00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:25.170
Don't do that, please. That's a hypertensive urgency.

233
00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:29.070
And actually, people are trying to get rid of that saying.

234
00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:32.910
It's just asymptomatic elevated blood pressure, all right?

235
00:10:32.910 --> 00:10:34.080
It's just asymptomatic, all right?

236
00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:38.640
It's the longstanding problem of hypertension,

237
00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:40.770
the longstanding problem of hypertension.

238
00:10:40.770 --> 00:10:43.500
The longstanding problem of hypertension

239
00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:46.530
does all these things in red, potential things in red.

240
00:10:46.530 --> 00:10:48.810
It gives you atherosclerotic disease in your brain

241
00:10:48.810 --> 00:10:51.270
and you get a thrombosis that can involve

242
00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:52.890
in the large vessels, your carotids,

243
00:10:52.890 --> 00:10:55.350
your middle cerebral, or your small vessels.

244
00:10:55.350 --> 00:10:58.830
Longstanding hypertension can cause Afib

245
00:10:58.830 --> 00:11:00.300
and your problems from there.

246
00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:03.630
Longstanding hypertension can cause a bleed

247
00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:05.160
in your brain, right?

248
00:11:05.160 --> 00:11:07.410
Those are the problem of longstanding hypertension,

249
00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:11.610
not that your blood pressure is 190 over 90 that day.

250
00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:13.860
Don't send them to me, please.

251
00:11:13.860 --> 00:11:15.063
Okay? All right.

252
00:11:16.380 --> 00:11:20.310
Afib, Afib, the problem I've already alluded to.

253
00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:22.200
You got a clot in your atrium,

254
00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:24.720
decides to go upstream, lands in your brain.

255
00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:27.570
All right, this is one slide I want you to take home.

256
00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:30.300
This is part of your take-home slides.

257
00:11:30.300 --> 00:11:33.480
There's three things you should know about Afib.

