Your brain's saying, "Let me get some blood up there

514
00:23:11.310 --> 00:23:15.240
and feed that penumbra, that watershed threatened area."

515
00:23:15.240 --> 00:23:16.073
All right?

516
00:23:16.073 --> 00:23:19.770
If it's above that value, then you have to titrate closely

517
00:23:19.770 --> 00:23:21.263
with nicardipine or labetalol.

518
00:23:22.830 --> 00:23:23.663
This is a slide.

519
00:23:23.663 --> 00:23:25.080
I just throw this in here for completeness sake.

520
00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:26.210
I don't think they'll ask it.

521
00:23:26.210 --> 00:23:28.170
If it's hemorrhagic stroke,

522
00:23:28.170 --> 00:23:30.720
you treat that blood pressure little more aggressively.

523
00:23:30.720 --> 00:23:31.820
That's all I'm saying.

524
00:23:32.700 --> 00:23:34.260
The treatment for ischemic stroke.

525
00:23:34.260 --> 00:23:36.720
What about aspirin? Just say, "Yes!"

526
00:23:36.720 --> 00:23:38.520
Yeah, it's time to get an antiplatelet on board.

527
00:23:38.520 --> 00:23:40.680
Yes, antipyretics. Treat the fever.

528
00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:41.910
Treat the glucose.

529
00:23:41.910 --> 00:23:45.360
Do a swallowing study before you feed them. Yes.

530
00:23:45.360 --> 00:23:48.030
Don't put them on any prophylactic antiseizure medicines.

531
00:23:48.030 --> 00:23:50.330
Don't start heparin, and don't start warfarin.

532
00:23:53.010 --> 00:23:55.473
All right, TIA. All right, let's talk about TIA.

533
00:23:56.610 --> 00:23:58.072
Here's the classic definition.

534
00:23:58.072 --> 00:24:01.348
You know how we all grew up with that 24-hour thing, right?

535
00:24:01.348 --> 00:24:03.750
You know, you had symptoms up to 24 hours,

536
00:24:03.750 --> 00:24:05.610
and then you went back to your baseline,

537
00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:07.350
and we said, "Oh, that's a TIA."

538
00:24:07.350 --> 00:24:08.977
And then there was a group that came along and said,

539
00:24:08.977 --> 00:24:11.880
"24 hours is silly. It really should be one hour."

540
00:24:11.880 --> 00:24:14.070
And the answer to that, both of those are out.

541
00:24:14.070 --> 00:24:14.903
Both of those are out.

542
00:24:14.903 --> 00:24:17.040
That's not the definition of TIA anymore.

543
00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:18.900
The definition of TIA is right here.

544
00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:20.910
It's a transient episode of neurologic dysfunction

545
00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:25.530
caused by some ischemia without infarction.

546
00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:29.730
So there's no time thing on the definition of TIA,

547
00:24:29.730 --> 00:24:32.190
and it is a tissue-based definition.

548
00:24:32.190 --> 00:24:34.560
In other words, the American Heart,

549
00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:36.217
American Stroke Association is saying,

550
00:24:36.217 --> 00:24:39.990
"We want you to prove to us that there's no stroke,

551
00:24:39.990 --> 00:24:42.330
there's no brain damage during that episode

552
00:24:42.330 --> 00:24:44.310
of someone who couldn't, you know, speak for a short time

553
00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:46.500
or had amaurosis fugax for a short time

554
00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:48.720
and then went back to their baseline."

555
00:24:48.720 --> 00:24:49.553
Why is that?

556
00:24:49.553 --> 00:24:52.140
Because if you take that person who had some amaurosis fugax

557
00:24:52.140 --> 00:24:54.937
or couldn't speak for 15 or 20 minutes and you said,

558
00:24:54.937 --> 00:24:57.450
"Oh, that's TIA, right? It's TIA."

559
00:24:57.450 --> 00:24:59.940
If you take them and you put them in the MRI machine

560
00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:02.100
and you do the diffusion-weighted images,

561
00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:04.200
you will see that that person

562
00:25:04.200 --> 00:25:06.150
who couldn't just speak for 15, 20 minutes,

563
00:25:06.150 --> 00:25:09.333
actually, about 1/3 of them actually stroked.

564
00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:11.420
They actually stroked.

565
00:25:12.360 --> 00:25:14.100
They'll have changes on their MRI

566
00:25:14.100 --> 00:25:16.893
saying there is cell death here,

567
00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:20.400
there's cell death here, so they actually stroked,

568
00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:23.370
and the longer their symptoms lasted,

569
00:25:23.370 --> 00:25:24.960
the greater their chance that you're gonna have

570
00:25:24.960 --> 00:25:26.760
a positive MRI.

571
00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:29.670
All right, that's why, and how does it show up

572
00:25:29.670 --> 00:25:31.140
on the diffusion-weighted images?

573
00:25:31.140 --> 00:25:35.070
Again, I look for white stuff. I look for the white stuff.

574
00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:39.090
So white stuff says there's cytotoxic edema and cell death.

575
00:25:39.090 --> 00:25:41.490
All right, so you have these transient neurological changes.

576
00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:45.930
You are encouraged, as soon as you can get hold of an MRI,

577
00:25:45.930 --> 00:25:49.170
okay, get them in, and you're encouraged to do it,

578
00:25:49.170 --> 00:25:52.980
and if the MRI is, quote, normal or the patient's baseline,

579
00:25:52.980 --> 00:25:54.210
it's a TIA.

580
00:25:54.210 --> 00:25:57.630
They didn't have any cell death versus they had cell death

581
00:25:57.630 --> 00:26:00.330
and they'll have a stroke.

582
00:26:00.330 --> 00:26:02.880
That's a stroke. All right.

583
00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:05.010
There are stroke and TIA mimics.

584
00:26:05.010 --> 00:26:08.610
You know, there's lots of stroke and TIA mimics.

585
00:26:08.610 --> 00:26:09.540
There's infection.

586
00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:11.940
There's, you know, the Todd paralysis after a seizure,

587
00:26:11.940 --> 00:26:13.920
complicated migraines, hypoglycemia.

588
00:26:13.920 --> 00:26:15.780
These all can mimic a stroke.

589
00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:17.850
This is how I lost all my hair in the ER,

590
00:26:17.850 --> 00:26:19.650
trying to figure out whether this patient

591
00:26:19.650 --> 00:26:22.560
had truly a stroke or it was something else, okay?

592
00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:24.210
'Cause I have to decide if it's not one of

593
00:26:24.210 --> 00:26:26.370
these other things, I have to give 'em tPA, et cetera.

594
00:26:26.370 --> 00:26:30.840
Okay, so what helps you distinguish

595
00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:33.420
whether it's stroke or a stroke mimic?

596
00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:36.180
When it comes to the anterior circulation,

597
00:26:36.180 --> 00:26:38.107
the neurologists like to teach and say,

598
00:26:38.107 --> 00:26:42.450
"Listen, anterior circulation stroke or TIA

599
00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:45.690
is associated a loss of something."

600
00:26:45.690 --> 00:26:49.680
I lost some motor strength. I lost some vision.

601
00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:54.363
I lost some speech. I lost something.

602
00:26:55.320 --> 00:27:00.320
If you gained something, I gained,

603
00:27:00.660 --> 00:27:03.150
I feel all this tingling in my hand now,

604
00:27:03.150 --> 00:27:06.570
I'm gaining tingling, all right, that's different.

605
00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:08.460
You don't wanna gain stuff.

606
00:27:08.460 --> 00:27:12.660
There's one loss that is not associated with a stroke,

607
00:27:12.660 --> 00:27:15.660
and that's loss of consciousness, okay?

608
00:27:15.660 --> 00:27:20.660
Syncope is not a TIA or a stroke, okay?

609
00:27:21.240 --> 00:27:24.420
Syncope is global hypoperfusion in the brain.

610
00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:25.830
You drop your blood pressure.

611
00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:28.080
You go boom. Down you go.

612
00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:30.180
You wake up after 30, 60 seconds.

613
00:27:30.180 --> 00:27:33.753
You're back to your baseline. That's syncope, all right?

614
00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:37.710
All right, secondary prevention of stroke and TIA.

615
00:27:37.710 --> 00:27:39.510
I've got just a couple of seconds left.

616
00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:41.010
I'm gonna go through this real quick.

617
00:27:41.010 --> 00:27:45.690
So you often will get patients back into your practice

618
00:27:45.690 --> 00:27:49.593
who were hospitalized for their stroke or their TIA,

619
00:27:50.490 --> 00:27:53.190
and now what are you supposed to do?

620
00:27:53.190 --> 00:27:55.110
Okay, how do you manage them secondarily

621
00:27:55.110 --> 00:27:57.420
'cause you don't want them to have another?

622
00:27:57.420 --> 00:28:00.420
So first, the diagnostic.

623
00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:02.340
We're gonna do four things, four slides.

624
00:28:02.340 --> 00:28:04.860
The diagnostic evaluation, all right,

625
00:28:04.860 --> 00:28:06.270
all this was probably done in the hospital,

626
00:28:06.270 --> 00:28:09.090
your ECG, your labs, yada, yada, yada.

627
00:28:09.090 --> 00:28:13.050
If it's an anterior circulation stroke,

628
00:28:13.050 --> 00:28:15.810
you should look for a potentially correctable cause.

629
00:28:15.810 --> 00:28:19.680
Now you look at the carotids, right?

630
00:28:19.680 --> 00:28:22.860
If this was a vertebrobasilar stroke,

631
00:28:22.860 --> 00:28:24.480
you don't look at the carotids.

632
00:28:24.480 --> 00:28:26.010
You have to look at the vertebrobasilar system

633
00:28:26.010 --> 00:28:30.060
with an MRA or a CTA, all right?

634
00:28:30.060 --> 00:28:33.150
That's the distinguishing factor there.

635
00:28:33.150 --> 00:28:35.550
The lifestyle changes. Yeah, you're gonna do all this.

636
00:28:35.550 --> 00:28:38.580
This is, again, that's the no-brainer part.

637
00:28:38.580 --> 00:28:40.560
You control the cholesterol, activities,

638
00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:43.320
smoking, alcohol, drug use, of course.

639
00:28:43.320 --> 00:28:45.330
Medical management.

640
00:28:45.330 --> 00:28:48.780
When do you start controlling the blood pressure?

641
00:28:48.780 --> 00:28:52.260
You can start that, like, day two or three in the hospital

642
00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:56.130
to now start slowly trying to drive their blood pressure

643
00:28:56.130 --> 00:28:59.040
back down below 130 over 80.

644
00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:01.620
You don't do it the first day, okay?

645
00:29:01.620 --> 00:29:04.440
You can control the lipids. Yes, you know that.

646
00:29:04.440 --> 00:29:06.690
The anti-platelet stuff, I've gotta do this real quick

647
00:29:06.690 --> 00:29:08.703
'cause this is so confusing.

648
00:29:11.010 --> 00:29:13.890
You have a patient who's had a TIA, a high-risk TIA,

649
00:29:13.890 --> 00:29:16.710
their ABCD score was high, okay?

650
00:29:16.710 --> 00:29:19.800
They have high risk or they had a minor stroke,

651
00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:22.893
which is defined as an NIHSS score less than three.

652
00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:26.817
You start them on dual antiplatelets,

653
00:29:26.817 --> 00:29:29.250
and it's based on two studies

654
00:29:29.250 --> 00:29:31.050
that I put in your supplement, okay?

655
00:29:32.100 --> 00:29:34.320
You put them on dual antiplatelets

656
00:29:34.320 --> 00:29:37.020
for three weeks to three months,

657
00:29:37.020 --> 00:29:39.180
three weeks to three months,

658
00:29:39.180 --> 00:29:41.850
and after those three weeks to three months,

659
00:29:41.850 --> 00:29:44.928
you go back to monotherapy.

660
00:29:44.928 --> 00:29:48.570
You don't stay on it lifelong, okay?

661
00:29:48.570 --> 00:29:50.910
So that's where dual antiplatelets come in.

662
00:29:50.910 --> 00:29:55.910
Now, counterintuitive, you have a big stroke, all right,

663
00:29:56.310 --> 00:29:59.940
large NIHSS score, I can't speak, I can't move half my body.

664
00:29:59.940 --> 00:30:02.070
I mean, that's a problem, right?

665
00:30:02.070 --> 00:30:04.263
There, you just get monotherapy.

666
00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:08.010
It's counterintuitive, I know.

667
00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:12.750
I'm less aggressive with the big bad stroke the patient had,

668
00:30:12.750 --> 00:30:15.930
but this minor stroke, I'm gonna be more aggressive,

669
00:30:15.930 --> 00:30:18.600
and that's based on the data, okay?

670
00:30:18.600 --> 00:30:21.390
Now, I'm gonna stress again on the left-hand side,

671
00:30:21.390 --> 00:30:24.060
I can't tell you how many patients,

672
00:30:24.060 --> 00:30:27.030
once they get placed on dual antiplatelets,

673
00:30:27.030 --> 00:30:32.030
stay on dual antiplatelets, and after a year or two,

674
00:30:32.220 --> 00:30:35.850
they come in to me with their hemorrhage.

675
00:30:35.850 --> 00:30:38.610
Okay, so understand that's what you're supposed to do.

676
00:30:38.610 --> 00:30:40.770
All right, people asked this in the Q&amp;A.

677
00:30:40.770 --> 00:30:43.680
Please don't ask this in the Q&amp;A 'cause I know it's coming.

678
00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:47.433
Well, what happens if they have their second or third TIA?

679
00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:50.820
Should I put them back on dual antiplatelets?

680
00:30:50.820 --> 00:30:53.570
Should I keep them on dual antiplatelets? What do I do?

681
00:30:55.230 --> 00:30:56.780
I don't have an answer for you.

682
00:30:57.630 --> 00:31:01.260
People do try increasing the doses,

683
00:31:01.260 --> 00:31:03.840
baby aspirin up to a full dose,

684
00:31:03.840 --> 00:31:05.490
say, "Hey, put you back on dual antiplatelets.

685
00:31:05.490 --> 00:31:07.200
Try a different antiplatelet regimen."

686
00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.870
There's no right answer, no right answer, okay?

687
00:31:09.870 --> 00:31:11.340
So please don't ask in the Q&amp;A.

688
00:31:11.340 --> 00:31:14.220
All right, last, carotid endarterectomy.

689
00:31:14.220 --> 00:31:16.080
Who do you recommend for carotid endarterectomy?

690
00:31:16.080 --> 00:31:21.060
With patients who have a non-disabling stroke

691
00:31:21.060 --> 00:31:25.140
or TIA in the ipsilateral side where the lesion was.

692
00:31:25.140 --> 00:31:26.700
So that's who you do it on.

693
00:31:26.700 --> 00:31:28.590
That's the long and short of it, okay,

694
00:31:28.590 --> 00:31:31.530
not on asymptomatic patients for the most part.

695
00:31:31.530 --> 00:31:34.590
So that's the secondary prevention of stroke and TIA,

696
00:31:34.590 --> 00:31:37.745
and I got to the end, and I'm gonna say thank you very much.

697
00:31:37.745 --> 00:31:40.328
